6
00:01:48,507 --> 00:01:50,543
Your move,
Dr. Watson.

7
00:02:14,967 --> 00:02:16,369
(<i> laughs under breath</i> )

8
00:02:17,369 --> 00:02:18,805
Mm-mm-mm-mm, mm.

9
00:02:21,840 --> 00:02:24,777
(<i> pager beeping</i> )

10
00:02:24,810 --> 00:02:26,879
Seasickness or coronary?

11
00:02:26,912 --> 00:02:29,348
Aw, I've got a few people
with the flu.

12
00:02:29,381 --> 00:02:30,416
Try not to cheat.

13
00:02:31,717 --> 00:02:32,852
Don't need to.

14
00:02:32,885 --> 00:02:35,188
(<i> music continuing</i> )

15
00:02:42,628 --> 00:02:44,897
Are you doing okay
with that, ma'am?

16
00:02:44,930 --> 00:02:46,599
What's going on?

17
00:02:46,632 --> 00:02:47,800
I don't know.

18
00:02:47,833 --> 00:02:49,835
You should check this.

19
00:02:49,868 --> 00:02:52,772
Do you have
any questions, ma'am?

20
00:02:52,805 --> 00:02:54,540
Is everything clear?

21
00:02:54,573 --> 00:02:57,377
WOMAN:
Is this my insurance
company here?

22
00:02:59,645 --> 00:03:01,280
Hello, Mr. Zelf.

23
00:03:01,313 --> 00:03:04,184
I understand you're not
feeling well this evening.

24
00:03:07,620 --> 00:03:10,590
Mr. Zelf?

25
00:03:10,956 --> 00:03:13,459
Mr. Zelf?

26
00:03:15,694 --> 00:03:17,296
Is it your stomach?

27
00:03:17,329 --> 00:03:18,497
Does your stomach hurt?

28
00:03:18,530 --> 00:03:20,333
Yes.

29
00:03:20,366 --> 00:03:22,969
(<i> breathing uneasily</i> )

30
00:03:23,002 --> 00:03:27,240
I'm going to get you
to lie down for me, Mr. Zelf.

31
00:03:27,273 --> 00:03:28,274
Okay?

32
00:03:28,307 --> 00:03:31,344
Swing your legs up.

33
00:03:31,377 --> 00:03:33,479
(<i> grunting</i> )

34
00:03:43,322 --> 00:03:45,524
Uh...

35
00:03:45,557 --> 00:03:48,293
I'm going to ask you
to sit back up

36
00:03:48,327 --> 00:03:49,595
Mr. Zelf.

37
00:03:49,628 --> 00:03:51,697
Yeah, there we go.

38
00:03:54,400 --> 00:03:57,303
All right.

39
00:03:57,336 --> 00:03:59,439
Open your mouth, please.

40
00:04:01,340 --> 00:04:03,243
And open your mouth wider.

41
00:04:11,450 --> 00:04:12,719
I need help!

42
00:04:16,488 --> 00:04:18,491
Get Thomas and Mary now!

43
00:04:25,731 --> 00:04:28,268
Oh, sweet mother of God!

44
00:04:32,071 --> 00:04:34,407
(<i> birds chirping</i> )

45
00:04:37,343 --> 00:04:38,611
Let's move in there.

46
00:04:38,644 --> 00:04:39,879
Okay, listen up.

47
00:04:39,912 --> 00:04:41,881
Special Agent Sullivan, FBI.

48
00:04:41,914 --> 00:04:44,917
We have a search warrant
pursuant to a court order.

49
00:04:44,950 --> 00:04:46,719
Please move
away from your desks

50
00:04:46,752 --> 00:04:47,987
and into the hallway.

51
00:04:48,020 --> 00:04:49,955
I'm the assistant office
manager, Kevin Poll.

52
00:04:49,988 --> 00:04:51,691
What's going on?

53
00:04:51,724 --> 00:04:53,626
It's insurance
fraud, Mr. Poll.

54
00:04:53,659 --> 00:04:55,394
Here's the
search warrant.

55
00:04:55,427 --> 00:04:57,663
We're seizing all the hospital's
financial records.

56
00:04:57,696 --> 00:04:59,365
All of them?

57
00:04:59,398 --> 00:05:00,466
I wouldn't wait up.

58
00:05:00,499 --> 00:05:01,934
Please, out
in the hallway.

59
00:05:01,967 --> 00:05:03,669
Uh, where's
your television?

60
00:05:03,702 --> 00:05:04,937
It's in the,
uh, cabinet.

61
00:05:04,970 --> 00:05:06,038
Over here?

62
00:05:06,071 --> 00:05:07,540
Yeah.

63
00:05:07,573 --> 00:05:08,840
Uh, what time is it, Peter?

64
00:05:08,874 --> 00:05:10,543
4:56.

65
00:05:10,576 --> 00:05:11,711
It's in there.

66
00:05:11,744 --> 00:05:13,713
All righty,
here we go.

67
00:05:13,746 --> 00:05:19,318
MAN (<i> over TV</i> ):
Reversing 11 years of policy
since the Gulf War

68
00:05:20,552 --> 00:05:22,021
Russia today signed
a formal treaty with Iraq

69
00:05:22,054 --> 00:05:25,825
reinstating the two countries'
historically close relationship.

70
00:05:25,858 --> 00:05:27,560
Come on, change the channel.

71
00:05:27,593 --> 00:05:29,395
What are you doing?
The game's on the other channel.

72
00:05:29,428 --> 00:05:30,963
Change the channel!

73
00:05:30,996 --> 00:05:32,631
SPORTSCASTER:
Mike Conlin steps
up to the plate.

74
00:05:32,664 --> 00:05:33,899
It's Chicago 5
and Florida 1.

75
00:05:33,932 --> 00:05:35,735
(<i> laughing</i> ):
5-1!

76
00:05:35,768 --> 00:05:37,570
5-1! Unstoppable!

77
00:05:37,603 --> 00:05:40,072
Can you believe it?
They're going to
sweep the playoffs.

78
00:05:40,105 --> 00:05:41,574
One more game, man!

79
00:05:41,607 --> 00:05:42,942
He delivers...
and that ball is gone!

80
00:05:42,975 --> 00:05:45,144
Yeah!

81
00:05:42,975 --> 00:05:45,144
Yeah!

82
00:05:45,177 --> 00:05:47,113
It is going. It is going.

83
00:05:47,146 --> 00:05:48,881
It is gone! Home run!

84
00:05:48,914 --> 00:05:50,549
Chicago in the Series.

85
00:05:50,582 --> 00:05:53,052
It's the end of the world
as we know it.

86
00:05:53,085 --> 00:05:54,686
Oh, I can't believe it.

87
00:05:54,720 --> 00:05:56,789
(<i> crickets chirping</i> )

88
00:06:26,151 --> 00:06:28,487
(<i> television playing</i>
 <i> indistinctly</i> )

89
00:06:28,520 --> 00:06:30,156
(<i> footsteps approaching</i> )

90
00:06:31,990 --> 00:06:34,093
(<i> phone ringing</i> )

91
00:06:42,067 --> 00:06:43,602
Hello?

92
00:06:43,635 --> 00:06:44,904
Yes, it is.

93
00:06:44,937 --> 00:06:48,107
What?

94
00:06:48,140 --> 00:06:51,644
Yeah.

95
00:06:51,677 --> 00:06:52,645
No, I understand.

96
00:06:52,678 --> 00:06:53,679
I got it.

97
00:06:53,712 --> 00:06:56,182
Yeah.

98
00:06:56,215 --> 00:06:58,784
Well, uh...
I don't mean to be forward

99
00:06:58,817 --> 00:07:02,121
but I'd appreciate a hint
of what this is abou...

100
00:07:04,756 --> 00:07:07,126
O'Hare, 2:45--
got it.

101
00:07:07,159 --> 00:07:09,128
(<i> chuckling sleepily</i> )

102
00:07:09,161 --> 00:07:11,764
Hey.

103
00:07:11,797 --> 00:07:14,166
I have to go to D.C.

104
00:07:14,199 --> 00:07:15,568
Why?

105
00:07:15,601 --> 00:07:16,602
I-I don't know.

106
00:07:16,635 --> 00:07:18,570
Plane leaves in an hour.

107
00:07:18,604 --> 00:07:20,005
I don't understand.

108
00:07:20,038 --> 00:07:22,174
I got to go to D.C.
Plane leaves in an hour.

109
00:07:22,207 --> 00:07:23,542
They won't tell me why.

110
00:07:23,575 --> 00:07:24,676
How can they
not tell you?

111
00:07:24,710 --> 00:07:25,878
By not telling me.

112
00:07:25,911 --> 00:07:27,746
But I got time off tomorrow.

113
00:07:27,779 --> 00:07:30,249
I cleared all my shifts
at the hospital.

114
00:07:30,282 --> 00:07:31,851
We were going to unpack.

115
00:07:31,884 --> 00:07:34,454
I know, but right now,
I got to go pack.

116
00:07:38,857 --> 00:07:40,793
Did they say when
you'd be back?

117
00:07:40,826 --> 00:07:42,962
Well, it better be
by Saturday.

118
00:07:42,995 --> 00:07:45,698
I've got those tickets
to game four.

119
00:07:45,731 --> 00:07:49,702
Hey, do you know where that,
um, the toilet bag thingy is?

120
00:07:49,735 --> 00:07:52,638
Someday, somehow,
we're going to have
to find the time

121
00:07:52,671 --> 00:07:53,906
to make this a home.

122
00:07:53,939 --> 00:07:55,140
What do you mean?
This is a home.

123
00:07:55,173 --> 00:07:56,709
We have a mortgage
to prove it.

124
00:07:56,742 --> 00:07:58,811
No, this is<i> house</i>
with a mortgage.

125
00:07:58,844 --> 00:08:01,647
We have to make it a<i> home</i>
with a mortgage.

126
00:08:01,680 --> 00:08:04,149
Uh-huh, and how do we do that?

127
00:08:04,182 --> 00:08:05,718
You know, by unpacking

128
00:08:05,751 --> 00:08:08,219
by putting up that mirror
in the hallway

129
00:08:08,253 --> 00:08:10,856
by hanging up curtains
and using this pepper shaker.

130
00:08:10,889 --> 00:08:12,825
Homes don't keep
pepper shakers in boxes.

131
00:08:12,858 --> 00:08:14,193
They keep them on tables.

132
00:08:14,226 --> 00:08:15,995
Well, then we'll have
to get a table.

133
00:08:16,028 --> 00:08:17,830
Exactly.

134
00:08:17,863 --> 00:08:19,798
Larry...

135
00:08:19,831 --> 00:08:21,534
there it is.

136
00:08:21,567 --> 00:08:23,802
Oh, there it is.

137
00:08:23,835 --> 00:08:24,971
Soon?

138
00:08:26,638 --> 00:08:28,039
Yes, soon.

139
00:08:42,287 --> 00:08:44,557
(<i> phones ringing</i> )

140
00:08:49,261 --> 00:08:51,531
(<i> voices speaking indistinctly</i> )

141
00:09:09,848 --> 00:09:10,782
Larry Sullivan.

142
00:09:10,816 --> 00:09:12,184
Hey.

143
00:09:12,217 --> 00:09:13,718
Hey, what're you doing here?

144
00:09:13,752 --> 00:09:14,853
I have no idea.

145
00:09:14,886 --> 00:09:16,822
Do you know
what's going on?

146
00:09:16,855 --> 00:09:18,824
Well, did you change units?

147
00:09:18,857 --> 00:09:21,226
No, no, I'm HHS--
mostly medical
fraud. You?

148
00:09:21,259 --> 00:09:22,161
DESC.

149
00:09:22,194 --> 00:09:23,728
DESC? What's that?

150
00:09:23,762 --> 00:09:26,297
Bio-terrorism,
under directive 3-9-N-16.

151
00:09:26,331 --> 00:09:29,835
On October 6, 2100 hours,
passengers and crew

152
00:09:29,868 --> 00:09:32,004
aboard the cruise ship<i>
 American Anthem</i>

153
00:09:32,037 --> 00:09:34,840
were taken sick by an
unknown infectious agent.

154
00:09:35,874 --> 00:09:37,009
The ship was off
the Mexican coast

155
00:09:37,042 --> 00:09:39,244
en route to San
Pedro, California.

156
00:09:39,277 --> 00:09:40,613
Two people have died.

157
00:09:40,646 --> 00:09:42,080
The symptoms are flu-like

158
00:09:42,114 --> 00:09:44,850
followed by internal
bleeding and convulsions.

159
00:09:44,883 --> 00:09:46,619
Initial findings suggest

160
00:09:46,652 --> 00:09:49,054
this may be a Marburg-type
outbreak.

161
00:09:49,087 --> 00:09:51,122
(<i> murmuring</i> )

162
00:09:49,087 --> 00:09:51,122
What's Marburg?

163
00:09:51,156 --> 00:09:53,659
It's a very
bad hot virus.

164
00:09:53,692 --> 00:09:55,260
It's not presently known
whether this is

165
00:09:55,293 --> 00:09:57,296
a natural outbreak
or a terrorist act.

166
00:09:57,329 --> 00:10:00,766
Coast Guard's quarantined
the ship off Long Beach

167
00:10:00,799 --> 00:10:02,668
and CDC is taking care
of the medical situation.

168
00:10:02,701 --> 00:10:04,036
Blake?

169
00:10:02,701 --> 00:10:04,036
Yes, sir?

170
00:10:04,069 --> 00:10:05,704
I want your unit in
the air by 1300 hours.

171
00:10:05,737 --> 00:10:07,740
You're to head up Hazmat
for the Western offices.

172
00:10:07,773 --> 00:10:10,009
You talk to Wilson about
contacts and details.

173
00:10:10,042 --> 00:10:11,777
Yes, sir.

174
00:10:11,810 --> 00:10:13,978
And remember,
there is no vaccine.

175
00:10:14,012 --> 00:10:15,180
There is no antidote.

176
00:10:15,213 --> 00:10:17,281
There's no treatment
for Marburg.

177
00:10:17,315 --> 00:10:18,317
So be careful.

178
00:10:18,350 --> 00:10:19,351
Be thorough.

179
00:10:19,384 --> 00:10:21,720
This is the real thing.

180
00:10:21,753 --> 00:10:23,222
Let's not screw it up.

181
00:10:23,255 --> 00:10:24,790
Questions?

182
00:10:24,823 --> 00:10:26,659
MAN:
Do we know
how the virus...?

183
00:10:26,692 --> 00:10:28,894
Do we have one
that works?

184
00:10:26,692 --> 00:10:28,894
(<i> overlapping speaking</i> )

185
00:10:28,927 --> 00:10:31,163
It's not doing us
any good sitting in
a lab in Aberdeen.

186
00:10:31,196 --> 00:10:33,165
If they got one
that works, I
want it onboard.

187
00:10:33,198 --> 00:10:34,867
What?

188
00:10:34,900 --> 00:10:37,102
Yes, I'm here to see
Assistant Director Farrell.

189
00:10:37,135 --> 00:10:38,804
What do you want me
to do?

190
00:10:38,837 --> 00:10:40,339
You want me to spray the crap
out of a ship

191
00:10:40,372 --> 00:10:42,241
that's sitting two miles
out in the ocean?

192
00:10:42,274 --> 00:10:43,175
Are you Sullivan?

193
00:10:43,208 --> 00:10:44,175
Yes, sir.

194
00:10:45,844 --> 00:10:48,047
Fine. Tell them I want
to get back to them.

195
00:10:48,080 --> 00:10:49,915
Thank you.

196
00:10:49,948 --> 00:10:52,818
Gentlemen, can we
have a couple of
minutes here, please?

197
00:10:55,721 --> 00:10:58,290
Sir, when'd you want
to contact Mexico City?

198
00:10:58,323 --> 00:10:59,959
Soon as I'm done here.

199
00:11:02,861 --> 00:11:05,698
MAN:
We also need to contact
the<i> Federales</i>

200
00:11:05,731 --> 00:11:08,300
and make sure we're
on the same page...

201
00:11:10,936 --> 00:11:12,137
Fraud, huh?

202
00:11:12,170 --> 00:11:13,305
Yes, sir.

203
00:11:15,207 --> 00:11:17,141
So you're probably not
too familiar

204
00:11:17,175 --> 00:11:18,977
with weapons
of mass destruction?

205
00:11:19,010 --> 00:11:22,148
Not unless you're referring
to HMOs.

206
00:11:26,218 --> 00:11:28,387
Do you know this man?

207
00:11:29,387 --> 00:11:31,156
Uh, yes.

208
00:11:31,189 --> 00:11:33,492
It's my uncle... uh, Uncle John.

209
00:11:33,525 --> 00:11:34,793
Are you close?

210
00:11:34,826 --> 00:11:36,295
Uh, not really, no.

211
00:11:36,328 --> 00:11:39,298
I haven't seem him in, uh...
well, a very long time.

212
00:11:39,331 --> 00:11:40,999
Why is that?

213
00:11:41,032 --> 00:11:42,334
My mother and my uncle
had a falling out

214
00:11:42,367 --> 00:11:43,468
after my father died.

215
00:11:43,502 --> 00:11:45,002
Did something happen to him?

216
00:11:45,036 --> 00:11:46,170
Yeah, he retired.

217
00:11:46,204 --> 00:11:47,739
Oh. From the Army?

218
00:11:47,773 --> 00:11:50,042
He lives on Bainbridge Island
off Seattle.

219
00:11:50,075 --> 00:11:51,443
It's crucial that
we talk to him.

220
00:11:51,476 --> 00:11:52,444
About what?

221
00:11:52,477 --> 00:11:54,446
Weaponization.

222
00:11:54,479 --> 00:11:58,984
This is a microscopic particle
that the CDC took off the lung

223
00:11:59,017 --> 00:12:02,187
of one of the
passengers who died.

224
00:12:02,220 --> 00:12:03,489
Question:

225
00:12:03,522 --> 00:12:05,124
is the particle a weapon?

226
00:12:07,559 --> 00:12:10,094
What do you need from my uncle?

227
00:12:10,128 --> 00:12:11,997
Don't you know who he is?

228
00:12:12,030 --> 00:12:13,966
Apparently not.

229
00:12:13,999 --> 00:12:15,968
Well... sweet ol' Uncle John

230
00:12:16,001 --> 00:12:18,871
personally invented
most of this stuff.

231
00:12:18,904 --> 00:12:22,241
He worked with the
Army's bio-weapons unit
in the '50s and '60s

232
00:12:23,141 --> 00:12:24,309
until Nixon disbanded it in '68.

233
00:12:24,342 --> 00:12:26,879
We have a generation gap
of knowledge.

234
00:12:26,912 --> 00:12:30,516
Men like your uncle, who truly
know about military bio-weapons

235
00:12:30,549 --> 00:12:32,518
have all either retired or died.

236
00:12:32,551 --> 00:12:34,153
They're known as fossils.

237
00:12:34,186 --> 00:12:36,922
We sent an agent out
from the Seattle office.

238
00:12:36,955 --> 00:12:38,957
Your uncle threatened
to shoot him.

239
00:12:38,990 --> 00:12:41,093
Apparently, he has
privacy issues.

240
00:12:41,126 --> 00:12:42,862
Good luck.

241
00:12:47,199 --> 00:12:48,300
Agent Blake?

242
00:12:48,333 --> 00:12:49,501
Yes.

243
00:12:49,534 --> 00:12:51,236
Donald Wells, CDC.

244
00:12:51,269 --> 00:12:52,571
This way.

245
00:12:52,604 --> 00:12:53,939
I'll take those, ma'am.

246
00:12:53,972 --> 00:12:55,107
Thank you.

247
00:12:55,140 --> 00:12:56,574
What's your setup?

248
00:12:56,608 --> 00:12:59,011
Looks like the interior
of the ship is level four.

249
00:12:59,044 --> 00:13:01,513
We have a negative airflow
and hepa filters in place.

250
00:13:01,546 --> 00:13:03,348
We've also
bleached down all surfaces.

251
00:13:03,381 --> 00:13:04,382
Noninfected

252
00:13:04,416 --> 00:13:06,018
are confined to cabins.

253
00:13:06,051 --> 00:13:08,587
The infected are in public
rooms under plastic tents.

254
00:13:08,620 --> 00:13:11,590
We're using the kitchen's
refrigerators as morgues.

255
00:13:11,623 --> 00:13:13,358
The Coast Guard's
running security.

256
00:13:13,391 --> 00:13:16,194
The Army's CBD Com has been
flying in men and supplies.

257
00:13:16,228 --> 00:13:17,563
What's the dead?

258
00:13:17,596 --> 00:13:19,198
33 and climbing.

259
00:13:21,633 --> 00:13:22,868
This is our level two.

260
00:13:22,901 --> 00:13:24,203
We suit up here.

261
00:13:34,579 --> 00:13:39,852
Welcome, Special Agent Blake,
to the<i> American Anthem</i> ballroom.

262
00:13:59,604 --> 00:14:02,875
(<i> patients coughing</i> )

263
00:14:40,345 --> 00:14:42,147
Ship's doctor.

264
00:14:42,180 --> 00:14:43,482
Airborne?

